data.content:
Here's the full migration. Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that all throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8:

| Found | Location | Pattern |
|-------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Control flow cleanup |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — replaces ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop cleanly; replaces ResetAbort + finally flow
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop — in .NET 8 there is no way to force it.
            // Log a warning; see pitfalls below.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## Key changes explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs (`WaitHandle`, async I/O) — a bool can't wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative cancellation; `Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated OCEs from other sources |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | No abort to reset — just exit the loop after cleanup |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping a fixed duration |
| — | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed to avoid timer/callback leaks |

## Critical pitfall: `GetNextItem()` must cooperate

Your comment says `GetNextItem()` "may block." This is the single biggest risk. If it blocks on something that ignores the token, `Cancel()` won't wake it and the thread hangs. You **must** make it cancellation-aware:

```csharp
// If it uses a BlockingCollection<T>:
var item = _queue.Take(token); // wakes on cancel, throws OCE

// If it polls with Thread.Sleep:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollInterval); // replaces Thread.Sleep

// If it does synchronous I/O (socket, DB):
// Switch to async overloads that accept CancellationToken,
// or use token.Register(() => socket.Close()) to unblock.
```

## Other pitfalls to watch for

| Pitfall | Mitigation |
|---------|------------|
| `FlushBuffers()` in `finally` still runs after cancellation | Verify it's safe to call during shutdown — this is preserved behavior |
| No forced kill available | If `GetNextItem` truly can't cooperate, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` |
| `CancellationTokenSource` leaked | Always `Dispose()` — hence the `IDisposable` pattern above |
| `OperationCanceledException` swallowed silently | Only catch at this top-level loop; let it propagate everywhere else in the call chain |
